Female: Brachypterous, rarely macropterous, always more robust than male; length 3.5–4.5, COLOR- ATION: As in male but hemelytra often uniformly dark brown to black, sometimes with yellowish line along basal half of cuneal fracture or with dirty yellow spots at base of cuneus; yellowish markings on hemelytra better expressed in macropterous females. SURFACE AND VESTITURE: As in male. STRUCTURE AND MEASUREMENTS: Body 2.5–3.5× as long as width of pronotum. Head : 1.2–1.3× as wide as high; vertex 2.5–3.0× as wide as eye; antennal segment II 0.7–1.2× as long as basal width of pronotum, 0.8–1.1× as long as width of head. Thorax : Pronotum 1.7–2.4× as wide as long and 0.9–1.3× as wide as head, with distinctly concave posterior margin; hemelytra ranging in length from reaching anterior part of abdominal tergum VII to almost covering entire abdomen, typically covering anterior half of abdominal tergum IX; clavus distinct, claval commissure as long as inner margin of clavus, cuneus in brachypterous specimens slightly delimited; posterior and lateral margins of hemelytra rounded or posterior margin sometimes truncate. GENITALIA: Sclerotized ring small, oval, medial sclerites almost straight, basally and apically tapering, large, at least twice as long as sclerotized rings (fig. 14); posterior wall of bursa copulatrix with uniformly sclerotized trapeziform sclerite, incision on the anterior margin narrow and not reaching middle of sclerite, anterior angles of this sclerite somewhat dentate, posterior margin without sclerites (fig. 18); sclerites encircling vulva curved and forming circle (as in fig. 19,
O. vittipennis
).
